 it is also notable for its community-based forms of cooperation and its high level of peasant political activity. The book presents a series of case studies that examine cooperative forms of organization in relation to developments in the regional economy and to changes in national policy. The analysis attempts to avoid interpreting local processes merely as responses to externally initiated change. It stresses instead the need to consider the interplay of local and national forces, because local groups and processes themselves affect the pattern of regional and national development. The case studies cover a range of political and economic topics, from peasant movements to the achievements and shortcomings of government-sponsored agricultural and manufacturing cooperatives. The concluding chapter, by the editors, explores the theoretical implications of these studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAgriculture, Cooperative-Peru. 0aPeasants-Peru. 0aPeru-Rural conditions. 0aRural development-Peru. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aGrondin, Marcelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aH., Pedro Cano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaite, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, Norman, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRoberts, Bryan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, Bryan R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSamaniego, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Gavin A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSáez, Juan Solano, eco